The restaurant has an open, airy decor with plenty of space between communal tables, which I loved! The service, however, left much to be desired. I stepped away from my reserved table and went to the bar to order a drink. I ended up waiting for over ten minutes before being able to give my order, and watched three others get served before me - including a man who walked up to the bar after I did. I essentially had to ask for someone to help me place my order before being told offhandedly that the bartender would take my order. I can’t be certain what was going on, but multiple people were working the bar at that time, including two or three active bartenders. Quite a few people behind the bar walked past me as I waited, with no one acknowledging I was there....and I’m the only person who looked like me that was standing at the bar at that time.  My friend - who was celebrating her birthday - frequents this spot and loves their food and the concept. It was my first time attending, and I’m very disheartened that this was my experience. I didn’t feel like it was the type of place I could give honest feedback about my experience, and did not feel comfortable until I left. I won’t be coming back.  Rated as a two because I’m not sure why such a serious slip of customer service could happen with so many people at the bar at that time. The redeeming quality was that the bartender who came to serve me adjusted the price of my drink due to missing ingredients.

I like the mix of stuff at 61 Local. It tries to be everything to everyone, and it’s not bad. It’s a decent coffee place, has beer and wine, and has interesting non-alcoholic bevs including ginger ale they make, lemonade, tea, and kombucha. The food menu is surprisingly good. The off-hour menu is quite limited, but there’s enough that someone who needs to eat will probably find something—some breakfast stuff and the truffle grilled cheese. The kombucha is okay, I wish they had flavors and it were more carbonated. The lemonade is a bit weak, but nicely flavored. The bar staff isn’t looking for people who want to order, so I really needed to walk over to them—eye contact won’t work. But they’re friendly enough once they deign to acknowledge you. There are a ton of people with laptops well into he late afternoon. I’ve also played board games there with friends. It can be a bit loud for that, but the long tables are nice. The front has high tables. Here are a couple of bike racks out front, but they could use more for nice weather times.
